 ==Social Manners==
 {{Cleanup-section|date=December 2007}}
 Ukrainians generally carry themselves in a very polite, civilized manner.{{fact|date=August 2009}} Men often hold the door open for a woman when she enters a building, stand up when a woman enters the room, and, if there is a shortage of seats, men will give up their seats to the women.{{fact|date=August 2009}} In rural areas, men will sometimes kiss a woman's hand, but this is starting to go out of fashion.<ref>{{cite book|coauthors=O. Bekh, J. M. Dingley|title=Ukrainian Phrasebook  |publisher=Lonely Planet |date=2005|isbn=9781741046052|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=E1QDn_T3CtIC&pg=PA48&dq=%22+kiss+a+woman%27s+hand%22+ukraine}}</ref>
- 
-According to convention, when standing at a threshold (doorsill), do not shake hands or offer anything to be taken by the person on the other side.{{fact|date=August 2009}} A young unmarried man or woman should not be seated at a table's corner.{{fact|date=August 2009}}  Always buy an odd number of flowers as a gift, unless it is a funeral.{{fact|date=August 2009}}  In that case, it is appropriate to buy an even number. When passing through the aisles in a theater or elsewhere, it is polite to face the people sitting down.{{fact|date=August 2009}}

